<br>
OK ... right (or not...)<br>
<br>
Cable television is made for people to enjoy.  How come that's not free?<br>
<br>
Video games are made for people to enjoy.  How come they're not free?<br>
<br>
I don't understand why people have this delusion that because music isn't something you can see or something you can hold in your hand that it should be free.  Musicians put just as much work into their work as do movie makers, book writers, and journalists.<br>
<br>
And none of them are giving their work away for free. <p>Chuck<br>
<a href="http://www.mp3.com/rmpsound">RMP Productions</a>
</p><span class=m><i></i></span><hr size=1><span class=m> </span></td></tr></table></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#FFFFFF><td colspan=2><table cellpadding=8 cellspacing=0 width=100%><tr><td nowrap width=20% valign=top><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub103.ezboard.com/udashofmilk.showPublicProfile?language=EN>DashOfMilk</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.users.dialstart.net/~dashland/html/parent.gif" BORDER=0> </span><br> <span class=usertitle>Shimmering Ocean<br /><img src=http://www.bbarden.com/img/levels/userlevel-5.gif /></span><br> <BR><img src=http://www.users.dialstart.net/~dashland/html/lene1b.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top width=80% class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.bbarden.com/img/em/puppydogeyes.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: AudioGalaxy - R.I.P.</span><br><span class=m><font color=#FF0000>Posted: 6/25/02 11:07:50 pm</font>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</span>    <hr size=1> *sigh*<br>
Okay...try and put it another way.<br>
<br>
I play sport. I play it because I enjoy it. The people I play with, play for their enjoyment... Some of the players... a very very small minority, are so good that they go on to get paid for what they do. They are paid a wage, to perform, but in the end - they still do it for their enjoyment. Do you think if they realised that the people who are watching them, are getting to see them for free, that they would complain? No... why should they..they still get paid, and in any case - its about enjoyment.<br>
<br>
The same applies equally to writers, actors, musicians and other artists. The work you produce if for your own, or others benefit or enjoyment. Sure it would be nice if you could get paid money to do what you love, but thats not whats its about. If your first intention as an artist is to make money out of what you, then, as I've said before, I don't think your an artist.<br>
<br>
Picking up on your examples.<br>
If I created tv programs as my hobby, then I would be absolutely delighted for it to be shown for free on cable tv.<br>
If I created a video game, I would love to give it to people, for them to enjoy.<br>
Both of these aren't free to the end user, because you have to pay for the packaging.. like paying for the production of CD, sleeve, box, marketing etc. The actuall products are free, from me the artist.<br>
There is a difference between being an artist and working to create art. Only a very few, very lucky people get paid to be an artist.... many get paid to work on art.<br>
I can freely share quote's or articles from journalists with friends, provided I am not gaining financially or otherwise. I can freely share my bought book with all my friends, and lastly I can freely pass my VHS video along to all my friends who can watch it. You see... the art is free.<br>
<br>
Finally there is also a big difference between enjoying art which the law says you acquired illegally, and downright piracy. Listening to a song I have downloaded, or even sharing with my friends.. is in my opinion completely and utterly harmless. Pirating this work is not harmless, as you are benefitting from someone else's graft financially. Of course I agree that in the interest of the music business piracy must stop...but this harms the people who are seriously interested in the music the most..<br>
<br>
You'll no doubt disagree - this isn't something we are going to see eye to eye on. But please do think too yourself, as an artist, what is your real aim?<br>
<br>
----------------------<br>
Ironically my brother came in half-way through typing this post and asked if I wanted to come see him play a gig next week. He wants £5, so I told him where to shove it. heh. I hear the rackett he makes every morning!!<br>
<br>
Dash <p><CENTER><HR>
Waiting for so long, for things that last eternally.<BR>
<IMG SRC="http://www.users.dialstart.net/~dashland/html/slidblue.gif"><BR><A HREF="http://go.ezboard.com/bbbarden/"> BBarden Network</A> -===- <A HREF="http://go.ezboard.com/btalkuk/"><B>TalkUK</B></A> -===- <A HREF="http://pub72.ezboard.com/bhashuk21885">#hashuk forums</A></CENTER></p><span class=m><i></i></span><hr size=1><span class=m> </span></td></tr></table></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CCE6FF><td colspan=2><table cellpadding=8 cellspacing=0 width=100%><tr><td nowrap width=20% valign=top><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub103.ezboard.com/ump3chuck.showPublicProfile?language=EN>MP3Chuck</A> </span><br> <span class=usertitle>Iceberg<br /><img src=http://www.bbarden.com/img/levels/userlevel-1-6.gif /></span><br> </td><td valign=top width=80% class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.bbarden.com/img/em/puppydogeyes.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: AudioGalaxy - R.I.P.</span><br><span class=m><font color=#FF0000>Posted: 6/25/02 11:35:20 pm</font>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</span>    <hr size=1> You're right, we aren't going to see eye to eye, so this is the last argument I'm going to make in this futile thread.<br>
<br>
Why should I not find it reasonable to try and recoup some of the losses I have from being a musician?  The music that comes from me, true, doesn't cost me a damn thing except time.  But being a musician costs money!  INstruments, recording time, recording media, equipment.  I'm by no means a professional, but that should not stop me from trying to gain back the thousands of dollars I've put into my music.  I think that's fair, don't you?<br>
<br>
And there is nothing you can do to justify your arguments because BY LAW YOU ARE NOT RIGHT.<br>
<br>
&quot;I can freely share quote's or articles from journalists with friends, provided I am not gaining financially or otherwise. I can freely share my bought book with all my friends, and lastly I can freely pass my VHS video along to all my friends who can watch it. You see... the art is free.&quot;<br>
<br>
That is a flawed argument.  While that's certainly allowable, it's because of Fair Use laws and nothign more.  One point I will make, though, is that if you pass on a video for a friend to view and he or she makes a copy of it, THAT is illegal.<br>
<br>
The main point I'm trying to make is that every aspect of being a creator (artist, musiciain etc...) costs money.  Until the creators of instruments and paint brushes and recording studios offer their goods and services for free, artists will have to find some way to gain back the money the put into their work.  WORK.  It may not be a 9 to 5 job, but it's work.<br>
<br>
So in closing:<br>
<br>
1 - KaZaA and other programs allow people to blatently break copyright law and mangles the process of artists recouping the loss they take through the creation of their works.<br>
<br>
2 - You cannot do whatever you want with a copyrighted work simply because you do not gain financially.  Again, I turn to the Fair Usage laws.  I'm not going to detail them, but if you'd like me to I will, 'cause I have the whole 250+ page US Copyright law right here.<br>
<br>
3 - Making music is not a free process, therefore musicians and artists have every right to charge a fee to allow other people to enjoy what is, in a legal sense, a musician's &quot;services.&quot;<br>
<br>
Case closed. <p>Chuck<br>
<a href="http://www.mp3.com/rmpsound">RMP Productions</a>
